ed Kingdom|UK]], have taken steps to ban the oral LD<sub>50</sub>, and the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) abolished the requirement for the oral test in 2001 (see Test Guideline 401, ''Trends in Pharmacological Sciences'' Vol 22, February 22, 2001).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Animal testing]]\n* [[Reed-Muench method]]\n*[[The dose makes the poison]] ([[Latin language|Latin]]: '''''sola dosis facit venenum)''''', the toxicology adage that high quantities of any substance is lethal, such as water.\n\n=== Other measures of toxicity ===\n{{div col}}\n* [[IDLH]]\n* [[Certain safety factor]]\n* [[Therapeutic index]]\n* [[Protective index]]\n* [[Fixed Dose Procedure]] to estimate LD50\n* [[Median toxic dose]] (TD50)\n* Lowest published toxic concentration (TCLo)\n* [[Lowest published lethal dose]] (LDLo)\n* [[EC50|EC<sub>50</sub>]] (half maximal effective concentration)\n* [[IC50|IC<sub>50</sub>]] (half maximal inhibitory concentration)\n* [[Draize test]]\n* [[Indicative limit value]]\n* [[No-observed-adverse-effect level]] (NOAEL)\n* [[Lowest-observed-adverse-effect level]] (LOAEL)\n* [[Up-and-down procedure]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Related measures ===\n* [[TCID50|TCID<sub>50</sub>]] Tissue Culture Infective Dosage\n* EID<sub>50</sub> Egg Infective Dosage\n* ELD<sub>50</sub> Egg Lethal Dosage\n* [[Plaque forming units]] (pfu)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ccohs.ca/oshanswers/chemicals/ld50.html Canadian Centre for Occupational Health and Safety]\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Lipnick RL, Cotruvo JA, Hill RN, Bruce RD, Stitzel KA, Walker AP, Chu I, Goddard M, Segal L, Springer JA | title = Comparison of the up-and-down, conventional LD50, and fixed-dose acute toxicity procedures | journal = Food and Chemical Toxicology | volume = 33 | issue = 3 | pages = 223\u201331 | date = March 1995 | pmid = 7896233 | doi = 10.1016/0278-6915(94)00136-C }}\n\n{{Pharmacology}}\n{{Toxicology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Median Lethal Dose}}\n[[Category:Animal testing]]\n[[Category:Toxicology]]\n[[Category:Mathematics in medicine]]\n", "name_user": "TOXRAMP", "label": "safe", "comment": "Specified that Carybdea rastonii is the species of Box jellyfish that produces CrTX-A, as the already present reference explains", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median_lethal_dose"}
{"title_page": "Calm (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Calm\n| type         = Studio\n| artist       = [[5 Seconds of Summer]]\n| cover        = 5 Seconds of Summer - Calm.png\n| alt          = A picture of all 5 Seconds of Summer members laying down on a black blanket hanging out with the word \"5SOS\" which is the short way to say \"5 Seconds of Summer\" and we see the letters \"C A L M\" underneath.\n| released     = {{start date|2020|3|27|df=y}}\n| studio       = \n| genre        = <!--Do not add unsourced genres -->\n| length       = 39:30\n| label        = \n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n| producer     = \n*[[Louis Bell]]\n*[[Charlie Puth]]\n*Happy Perez\n*[[Andrew Watt (musician)|Andrew Watt]]\n*Matthew Pauling\n*Dre Moon\n*[[Oscar Gorres]]\n*[[Benny Blanco]]\n| prev_title   = [[Meet You There Tour Live]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Calm\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Easier (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Easier]]\n | single1date = 23 May 2019\n | single2     = [[Teeth (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Teeth]]\n | single2date = 21 August 2019\n | single3     = [[No Shame (5 Seconds of Summer song)|No Shame]]\n | single3date = 5 February 2020\n | single4     = [[Old Me (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Old Me]]\n | single4date = 6 March 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiodate.it/radio-date/5-seconds-of-summer-old-me-200266-06-03-2020-radiodate/|title=5 Seconds to Summer - Old Me (Radio Date: 06-03-2020)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303015331/http://radiodate.it/radio-date/5-seconds-of-summer-old-me-200266-06-03-2020-radiodate/|accessdate=3 March 2020|archivedate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n| single5      = [[Wildflower (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Wildflower]]\n| single5date  = 25 March 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/5-Seconds-Of-Summer-Release-New-Single-Wildflower-20200325|title=5 Seconds of Summer Release New Single \"Wildflower\" |website=Broadway World|date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Wildflower Meaww\">{{cite web|url=https://meaww.com/5-seconds-of-summer-calum-hood-wildflower-single-lyric-video-album-calm|title=5 Seconds of Summer's Calum Hood drops single \"Wildflower\" lyric video ahead of ''CALM'' album release|website=Meaww|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''Calm''''' (stylised as '''''C A L M''''', an\u00a0acronym of the first letters of the band members' names, Calum, Ashton, Luke and Michael)<ref name=\"Gigwise\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/reviews/3375064/album-review-5-seconds-of-summer-calm|title=Album Review: 5 Seconds Of Summer - CALM|work=[[Gigwise]]|last=Padin|first=Malvika|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\" /> is the fourth studio album by Australian [[pop rock]] band [[5 Seconds of Summer]], released on 27 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/5-seconds-of-summer-no-shame-lyric-video-calm-release-date/|title=5 Seconds of Summer Drop ''Calm'' Album Details with Single \"No Shame\"|work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]|last=Quiles|first=Alyssa|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> Due to a shipping error, around 10,000 copies of the album were released early in the US, subsequently allowing the album to chart a week before it was due.<ref>{{cite tweet|url=https://twitter.com/5SOS/status/1244667175375257609?s=19|title=5 Seconds of Summer announcement|author=5 Seconds of Summer (verified account)|user=5SOS|number=1244667175375257609|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the album's release, the band released a four-track \"Relaxation\" remix collection via the meditation app, Calm. The collection features each bandmember reimagining a different track off the album in collaboration with producer Matt Pauling: guitarist Michael Clifford on \"Easier\", bassist Calum Hood on \"Old Me\", drummer Ashton Irwin on \"Red Desert\", and guitarist and vocalist Luke Hemmings on \"Best Years\".<ref name=\"BillboardCalm\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/pop/9344500/5-seconds-of-summer-calm-stream-it-now|title=Stay 'CALM,' 5 Seconds of Summer's New Album Has Arrived|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nThe album was announced on the band's social media on 5 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/5-seconds-of-summer-calm-no-shame-948179/|title=5 Seconds of Summer Announce New Album ''Calm'', Drop \"No Shame\"|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> A few days earlier, the band also confirmed that they will embark on the [[No Shame Tour (5 Seconds of Summer)|No Shame Tour]] to support the album, set to kick off in May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/live/8549774/5-seconds-summer-north-american-no-shame-tour-dates|title=5 Seconds of Summer Have 'No Shame' Tour Set for North America: See the Dates|last=Mims|first=Taylor|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background and inspiration==\nThe band were inspired by a lot of [[industrial music]] whilst working on the album, which helped them achieve a \"[[rhythmic|rhythm]] side\" on the songs, and in turn lends to the melodic writing and the melodic process. Drummer Ashton Irwin explained: \"As far as [[acoustics|sonic]] inspirations go, we always try to incorporate some of what everyone is actually listening to so it's a more genuine and influenced record that we can speak on.\" The album contains a \"lighter\" sound in comparison to the band's previous work. Rhythm guitarist Luke Hemmings said he felt like the [[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer album)|last album]] was \"pretty heavy and dark [...] Whereas this one has that side of it with the lighter side of life and moving forward rather than being stuck in one place\".<ref name=\"Herald & Review\">{{Cite web|url=https://herald-review.com/people/seconds-of-summer-inspired-by-industrial-music-on-new-album/article_1d9b84ed-b3e0-523e-b7c0-6a03c68ae855.html|title=5 Seconds of Summer inspired by industrial music on new album CALM|work=[[Herald & Review]]|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The band's bassist Calum Hood said most of the credit is owed to vocalist Luke Hemmings, whose lyrics, Hood said, \"tell the tale of a man who has matured over the years and who has really honed in on his craft\". Hood, however, noted:\u00a0\"I think everyone had something to say with this album, in terms of their coming of age - in really reflecting on the people who we were and how things shaped us, and who we want to become in the future.\" He futher described the album as \"pretty chaotic at times\".<ref name=\"ABC\">{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2020/3/30/with-new-album-c-a-l-m-5-seconds-of-summer-says-they-werent.html|title=With new album 'C A L M,' 5 Seconds of Summer says they \"weren't afraid of pushing the\u00a0boundaries\"|website=[[ABC News Radio]]|last=Dresdale|first=Andrea|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and composition==\nAmelia Parreira of ''Riff'' magazine summarized the album, saying 5 Seconds of Summer bring forth\u00a0a \"new musical density and electrifying nuance on\u00a0''Calm'', with a misleading name for a body of work that is anything but sonically mellow\". \nThe album's opening track, the \"groovy, anthemic\" \"Red Desert\" hinges on psychedelia, with the \"gospel-like vocals\" of Luke Hemmings. The song contains light bass vibration from bassist Calum Hood. The song's theme is about \"contentment and falling in love\", which Parreira noted sets the album's tone. Track 2, \"No Shame\" features a \"retro [[1980s in music|'80s pop]] vibe\", layered with \"explosive instrumentals over meaningful lyrics and raw stories\". Hemmings delivers high notes on the song. \"Old Me\", lyrically reflects on past mistakes, and is a high-energy \"dance anthem\". [[Easier (5 Seconds of Summer song)|\"Easier\"]], released as the album's lead single, has a conversational tone, with \"mellow\" electro instrumentation. Second single [[Teeth (5 Seconds of Summer song)|\"Teeth\"]], is a [[grunge|grungy]], rock-tinged song, with an energetic, catchy chorus. Wildflower\", similarly to \"No Shame\", is reminiscent of '80s pop, consisting of a \"[[The Beach Boys|Beach Boys]]-like vocal chant before a rise in bass and [[synth-pop|synth]] undertones set a romantic tone on the verses\". \"Best Years\" move at a slower pace, albeit containing a \"danceable vibe\". The piano-led \"Lover of Mine\" features intertwining guitar strumming patterns and \"powerful vocal styles\". \"Thin White Lies\" is an \"angst-ridden\" dance-esque track, with \"strong electric beats\". The album concludes with the slow-burner \"Lonely Heart\" and the self-reflcetive \"High\", both ballads, with slightly energetic production, marking a \"calm end\" to the album.\n\nSources:<ref name=\"Riff Mag\">{{Cite web|url=https://riffmagazine.com/album-reviews/5-seconds-of-summer-5sos-calm/|title=Album review: 5 Seconds of Summer bring high energy to 'CALM'|work=Riff magazine|last=Parreria|first=Amelia|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gigwise\" />\n\n==Singles==\nThe album's lead single, \"[[Easier (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Easier]]\", was released via [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] on 23 May 2019. The second single, \"[[Teeth (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Teeth]]\" was released on 21 August 2019 and was also included in the ''13 Reasons Why: Season 3 (Music from the Original TV Series)'' soundtrack. \"[[No Shame (5 Seconds of Summer song)|No Shame]]\" was released as the third single on 5 February 2020, alongside the album announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550208/5-seconds-of-summer-no-shame-calm-album|title=5 Seconds of Summer Reveal New Song \"No Shame\", Announce ''Calm'' Album: See When It's Coming|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> \"[[Old Me (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Old Me]]\", originally released on 21 February 2020 as the first promotional single from the album, was released to radio on 6 March 2020 as the album's fourth single.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/charts/singles-to-radio/|title=Singles to Radio|website=The Music Network|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> \"[[Wildflower (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Wildflower]]\" was released as the album's fifth single on 25 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/5SOS/status/1242663471805657088|title=5 Seconds of Summer on Twitter: Wildflower out now|via=[[Twitter]]|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Wildflower Meaww\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = auspOp\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"auspOp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2020/03/calm-yourself-david-checks-out-the-5sos-album/|title=Calm Yourself, David Checks Out the 5SOS Album|work=auspOp|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| rev2Score = 8/10<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|last=Raza-Sheikh|first=Zoya|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/5-seconds-of-summer-calm|title=5 Seconds Of Summer - CALM|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\nDavid from ''auspOp'' said \"The title gives away the general feel of this album \u2013 personal and a bit more subdued\" saying the album \"takes a melodic approach, but is no less engaging or listenable.\"<ref name=\"auspOp\"/>\nMalvika Padin of ''[[Gigwise]]'' gave the album a positive review, writing: \"Despite that niggling urge to skip the odd mediocre track, the desire to play beauties like 'High' on loop wins in the end and ''Calm'' stands on a pedestal of near-perfection pop\". Padin noted how the album is \"split into two distinct, yet cohesive, sections of music that are authentically 5SOS\" and labeled the album \"a look into the journey of four young boys growing up and getting pulled into the addictive power of fame\".<ref name=\"Gigwise\" />\n\n==Commercial Performance==\n\nCalm debuted atop the [[UK Albums Chart]], with first week sales nearly 35,000 units and 550 copies ahead of [[Dua Lipa]]'s ''[[Future Nostalgia (Dua Lipa album)|Future Nostalgia]]'', becoming their second number one album in the country, since the release of [[Sounds Good Feels Good]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/entertainment/uk-singles-chart/news/5-seconds-of-summer-beat-dua-lipa-to-albums-top-spot_395317.html |title= 5 Seconds Of Summer beat Dua Lipa to albums top spot|</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nTrack listing and credits adapted from [[Apple Music]] metadata.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/calm/1497416763|title=Calm by 5 Seconds of Summer on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> Additional credits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/129734508|title=No Shame / 5 Seconds of Summer \u2013 Tidal|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/109591539|title=Easier / 5 Seconds of Summer \u2013 Tidal|website=Tidal|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/115983693|title=Teeth / 5 Seconds of Summer \u2013 Tidal|website=Tidal|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = Red Desert\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[5 Seco