d turns many local dogs into vicious killers.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Rob Morrow]] as Dave\n* [[Kelly Rutherford]] as Sara\n* [[Tristin Mays]] as Rosalyn\n* [[Carmen Tonry]] as Danielle\n* [[Jill Zarin]] as Liz\n* [[Mary Katherine O'Donnell]] as Alice Wise\n* [[B.D. Boudreaux]] as Bill\n* [[Mason Guccione]] as Casey\n* [[Darrell Chumley]] as Chester\n* [[Eric Ashton Spooner]] as Firefighter Eddie\n* [[Dalton Alfortish]] as Ray\n* [[Shanna Marie Burris]] as Misty\n* [[Dylan Vox]] as Seth\n* [[Christin Rankins]] as Groomer\n* [[Andre Bauth]] as Sandoval\n* [[Maria Robles]] as Kim\n\n== Reception ==\nThe film received negative reviews, currently holding a 2.9 on the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4926042/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|4926042}}\n\n{{Eric Red}}\n\n[[Category:2015 horror films]]\n[[Category:2015 television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eric Red]]\n[[Category:Horror television films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-horror-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bovineboy2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "change category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_of_the_Wild"}
{"title_page": "Rasoul Najafian", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = Rasoul Najafian.jpg\n|imagesize = 200px |\n| name                    = Rasoul Najafian\n| birthname               = \n| birth_date               = 1952\n| birth_place              = [[Tehran]], Iran \n| othername               = \n| occupation              = Actor, director and singer\n| yearsactive             =\n| spouse                  = \n| website                 = \n}}\n'''Rasoul Najafian'''''( [[Persian Language|in Persian]] : \u0631\u0633\u0648\u0644 \u0646\u062c\u0641\u06cc\u0627\u0646)'' born in 1952 in Tehran is an Iranian actor, director and singer.\n\n== Biography==\nRasoul Najafian was born in 1952 in Tehran. Although he studied psychology at the university, his passion was Art. He learned the theory and practice of music with masters like Mehrtash. He also studied acting and directing for four years with Mostafa Oskouei and later became his assistant.\n\n== Career==\nHe started his acting career by playing small roles in plays produced and directed by Oskouei. He directed the play ''Sisyphe et la mort'' written by Robert Merle in 1973. The next year his short film ''Papoli Jan'' won the first prize of the ABU Asian Film Festival. In 1975 he took an adaptation of Dostoevsky's ''Crime and Punishment'' to the stage. His first work as a director on Television was ''The Elevator'' (1983), written by Hossein Panahi. Playing the role of Amir Nejati, caught in the governmental bureaucracy, in this piece brought Najafian fame and for many years people recalled him by that name. In the sixties he and Panahi collaborated in writing and directing many tele-theaters such as ''Flower and Spring'' (1984),''Two Ducks in the Mist'' (1985), ''American Style'' (1986), ''Like a Smile'' (1991). He was one of the writers of one of the most popular television series in Iran ''Ziba Barbershop'' (1994) directed by Marzieh boroumand. He adapted [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]]'s short stories for tele-theater in 1989 and directed them for channel 2.\n\nHe has worked as an actor with directors such as Behrouz Afkhami in ''Mirza Kuchak Khan'' (1983), and Davood Mirbagheri in ''The Wolves'' (1985) and ''Ra'na'' (1986). He worked later with Mirbagheri on stage where he performed in one of the lead roles in ''Loveville'' (\u0639\u0634\u0642 \u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f) (1996) which is among the most commercially successful plays in Iran.\n\nIn 1988 Najafian worked as the assistant to the director Saeid Ebrahimifar in the critically acclaimed movie ''Fire and Reed'' (\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u0646\u06cc). In the following year, Najafian worked with Shahriar Parsipour as assistant director in the movie ''Image of Love'' (\u0646\u0642\u0634 \u0639\u0634\u0642); he also composed its score for which he was nominated for the best music score in the Fajr Film Festival.\n\nThis nomination motivated him to concentrate more on music till in 1997 his first album ''Bibi Jan'' was released. This was a turning point in his life as from then on his voice was the trademark of his fame rather than his face. He continued his acting career in TV series Cactus 1 and Cactus 2 directed by Mohammadreza Honarmand.\n\nHe is currently working on a big project concerning Iranian folklore music in different categories such as lullabies, mourning songs, etc.\n\n== Filmography==\n*Mirza Kuchak Khan\n*The Wolves\n*Ra'na\n*Fire and Reed\n*\n*Khodro Tehran 11\n*Cactus\n* [[Marde Hezar Chehreh]] ''(Thousand-Face Man)''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mehran Modiri]]\n* [[Siamak Ansari]]\n* [[Saed Hedayati]]\n* [[Nasrollah Radesh]]\n* [[Saeid Pirdoost]]\n* [[Reza Feiz Noroozi]]\n* [[Shervin Najafian]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://archive.is/20050430034945/http://www.parsimusic.com/en/ Rasoul Najafian]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Najafian, Rasoul}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = Rasoul Najafian.jpg\n|imagesize = 200px |\n| name                    = Rasoul Najafian\n| birthname               = \n| birth_date               = 1951\n| birth_place              = [[Tehran]], Iran \n| othername               = \n| occupation              = Actor, director and singer\n| yearsactive             =\n| spouse                  = \n| website                 = \n}}\n'''Rasoul Najafian'''''( [[Persian Language|in Persian]] : \u0631\u0633\u0648\u0644 \u0646\u062c\u0641\u06cc\u0627\u0646)'' born in 1951 in Tehran is an Iranian actor, director and singer.\n\n== Biography==\nRasoul Najafian was born in 1951 in Tehran. Although he studied psychology at the university, his passion was Art. He learned the theory and practice of music with masters like Mehrtash. He also studied acting and directing for four years with Mostafa Oskouei and later became his assistant.\n\n== Career==\nHe started his acting career by playing small roles in plays produced and directed by Oskouei. He directed the play ''Sisyphe et la mort'' written by Robert Merle in 1973. The next year his short film ''Papoli Jan'' won the first prize of the ABU Asian Film Festival. In 1975 he took an adaptation of Dostoevsky's ''Crime and Punishment'' to the stage. His first work as a director on Television was ''The Elevator'' (1983), written by Hossein Panahi. Playing the role of Amir Nejati, caught in the governmental bureaucracy, in this piece brought Najafian fame and for many years people recalled him by that name. In the sixties he and Panahi collaborated in writing and directing many tele-theaters such as ''Flower and Spring'' (1984),''Two Ducks in the Mist'' (1985), ''American Style'' (1986), ''Like a Smile'' (1991). He was one of the writers of one of the most popular television series in Iran ''Ziba Barbershop'' (1994) directed by Marzieh boroumand. He adapted [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]]'s short stories for tele-theater in 1989 and directed them for channel 2.\n\nHe has worked as an actor with directors such as Behrouz Afkhami in ''Mirza Kuchak Khan'' (1983), and Davood Mirbagheri in ''The Wolves'' (1985) and ''Ra'na'' (1986). He worked later with Mirbagheri on stage where he performed in one of the lead roles in ''Loveville'' (\u0639\u0634\u0642 \u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f) (1996) which is among the most commercially successful plays in Iran.\n\nIn 1988 Najafian worked as the assistant to the director Saeid Ebrahimifar in the critically acclaimed movie ''Fire and Reed'' (\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u0646\u06cc). In the following year, Najafian worked with Shahriar Parsipour as assistant director in the movie ''Image of Love'' (\u0646\u0642\u0634 \u0639\u0634\u0642); he also composed its score for which he was nominated for the best music score in the Fajr Film Festival.\n\nThis nomination motivated him to concentrate more on music till in 1997 his first album ''Bibi Jan'' was released. This was a turning point in his life as from then on his voice was the trademark of his fame rather than his face. He continued his acting career in TV series Cactus 1 and Cactus 2 directed by Mohammadreza Honarmand.\n\nHe is currently working on a big project concerning Iranian folklore music in different categories such as lullabies, mourning songs, etc.\n\n== Filmography==\n*Mirza Kuchak Khan\n*The Wolves\n*Ra'na\n*Fire and Reed\n*\n*Khodro Tehran 11\n*Cactus\n* [[Marde Hezar Chehreh]] ''(Thousand-Face Man)''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mehran Modiri]]\n* [[Siamak Ansari]]\n* [[Saed Hedayati]]\n* [[Nasrollah Radesh]]\n* [[Saeid Pirdoost]]\n* [[Reza Feiz Noroozi]]\n* [[Shervin Najafian]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://archive.is/20050430034945/http://www.parsimusic.com/en/ Rasoul Najafian]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Najafian, Rasoul}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Iranian male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Alishahss75ali", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rasoul_Najafian"}
